../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:5:source: exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit, strategy-001
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Exact-NS No-Near-Closed-Tao-Circuit: Missionary Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:10:## Mission Type
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:12:Mechanism-to-theorem mission: take a qualitative discrepancy and decide whether it sharpens into one exact mathematical object that can be proved, refuted, or killed at the definition layer.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:14:## What the Methodology Was
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:18:- Phase 0 definition gate for a "near-closed Tao circuit"
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:19:- Phase 1 exact-support audit on the smallest honest helical object
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:20:- Phase 2 refine-or-stop test for the packetized backup
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:22:Three explorations were enough because the mission's real bottleneck was object definition, not long downstream proof work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:24:## What Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:26:### Phase 0 was correctly framed as "define one theorem-facing object," not "collect possible formalisms"
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:28:Exploration 001 forced the mission to separate exact NS data from user-chosen tolerances and to name one preferred singleton-support object plus one backup. That prevented the usual failure mode where a mechanism mission drifts among several partially compatible definitions.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:30:**Generalizable lesson:** For mechanism-formalization missions, require exactly one preferred exact object and at most one backup. If the strategizer cannot do that, the mission is not ready for quantitative work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:32:### Auditing the smallest exact support first was the highest-leverage move
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:36:**Generalizable lesson:** When a mission proposes an exact interaction graph, test static embeddability on the smallest exact support before any quantitative coefficient campaign. Geometry can kill the object much earlier than analysis.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:38:### The refine-or-stop pass on the backup saved the mission from fake progress
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:40:Once the singleton object failed, exploration 003 did the right thing: it did not treat packetization as automatic continuation. It asked whether the packet backup still defined one canonical exact object. The answer was no, so the mission stopped cleanly instead of spending more budget on support engineering disguised as theorem work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:42:**Generalizable lesson:** If a fallback object introduces new choices in support, projection, leakage scalarization, or reconstruction convention, run a dedicated canonization gate immediately. If canonization fails, stop. Do not call that "Phase 2 progress."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:44:### One strategy was sufficient because the question was genuinely binary
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:48:**Generalizable lesson:** For exact-object existence questions, default to one strategy unless the first strategy leaves a sharply defined surviving target. Multi-strategy arcs are for surviving objects, not for vague backups.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:50:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:52:### Canonical packet-model requirements should have been prescribed upfront
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:56:- fixed support convention,
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:57:- fixed projection/coordinatization,
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:58:- fixed desired-vs-leakage bookkeeping,
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:59:- fixed network-restoration rule.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:63:### "Static closure audit before coefficient audit" should be a named cross-phase rule
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:65:The strategy benefited from this implicitly, but it deserves to be explicit. Similar missions will otherwise jump straight to computing coefficients on an impossible support.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:67:## Surprising Findings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:71:3. Three explorations were enough. For definition-gated missions, brevity is often a sign of good targeting rather than shallow work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:73:## Lessons That Generalize
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-learnings.md:75:1. Definition-gated missions need one preferred exact object, not a menu of formalisms.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:2:topic: phased foundation-then-comparison methodology for hypothesis-testing missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Thermal Time Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:10:## What was prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:12:Three-phase methodology: Phase 1 (foundation + survey, explorations 1-3), Phase 2 (head-to-head computation, explorations 4-7), Phase 3 (sharpen or pivot, explorations 8-10). Cross-cutting rule: "explorers must compute." Validation criteria aligned to mission tiers. Specific computational targets named (Rindler, coupled oscillators, CFT interval).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:14:## What happened
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:16:The strategizer used 4 explorations total (2 Phase 1, 2 Phase 2) and reached a clean conclusion: TTH has no novel testable content for non-relativistic equilibrium systems. The strategizer correctly stopped early rather than padding. Phase 3 was never needed.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:18:## What worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:22:2. **Phased approach with clear completion criteria was effective.** The strategizer knew when Phase 1 was done (modular Hamiltonians computed, normalization resolved) and transitioned cleanly to Phase 2. The criteria prevented both premature and excessive exploration.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:26:4. **The strategizer was efficient.** 4 explorations to a definitive result is excellent. The REASONING.md shows clear self-correction (catching the wrong baseline comparison after exploration-002).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:28:## What didn't work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:32:2. **The local-vs-global interpretation question was left too late.** This was THE critical disambiguation, and the strategizer correctly identified it as urgent after exploration-003. But the strategy should have forced this question into Phase 1 as a mandatory milestone. Lesson: for hypothesis-testing missions, interpretation questions must be resolved BEFORE computing consequences.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:36:## Generalizable lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:38:- **Interpretation questions are blocking.** In hypothesis-testing missions, if the hypothesis has an ambiguity (local vs global, normalization convention, etc.), resolving that ambiguity is more important than any computation. Make it Phase 1, Task 1.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:40:- **"Negative results in the obvious regime" strategies are efficient but leave the interesting territory untouched.** Strategy-001 efficiently proved that the non-relativistic regime is uninteresting — but the mission actually requires exploring the covariant regime. First strategies should budget at least one probe into the hardest/most interesting territory, even if the foundation isn't perfect yet.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:42:- **4 explorations can be sufficient for a definitive conclusion.** If the question is clear and the methodology is right, you don't need 10 explorations. The strategizer's judgment to stop after a clean negative result (rather than padding) was correct.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-thermal-time-learnings.md:44:- **Pre-specify the comparison baseline explicitly.** Exploration-002 compared local TTH against the *free* oscillator (wrong baseline) instead of the *coupled* Hamiltonian (right baseline). The strategy should have been explicit: "C_full_QM means Tr[ρ_AB x_A(τ) x_A(0)] with x_A(τ) evolved under the FULL H_AB."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:2:topic: Three-phase decompose-construct-verify pipeline for proof problems
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:8:# Strategy 001 Learnings: Yang-Mills Conjecture
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:10:## What methodology was prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:12:A three-phase **Decompose-Construct-Verify** pipeline with 10-exploration budget:
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:13:- Phase 1: Three parallel algebraic decompositions (different mathematical lenses)
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:14:- Phase 2: Synthesis → proof attempt → mandatory adversarial → second attempt
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:15:- Phase 3: Consolidation
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:19:## How well it worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:21:**Extremely well.** 8 of 10 explorations used, produced a complete proof of a significant partial case plus precise gap characterization. The result (Combined Bound Lemma + cube-face inequality) was genuinely novel.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:23:**Phase 1 (parallel decompositions) was the star.** All three explorations produced complementary findings. The cube-face grouping (E002) became the proof route, but E001's single-link theorem and E003's parallelogram identity provided structural support. Running them in parallel was high-value — each took ~1h and none depended on the others.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:25:**Phase 2 adaptation was critical.** E005 stalled (47 min extended thinking), producing no proof but a KEY reformulation (3×3 matrix). The strategizer correctly deviated from the prescribed sequence (was supposed to do adversarial review next, but there was nothing to review), and instead launched E006 as a focused proof attempt that SUCCEEDED. This adaptation — repurposing the adversarial slot for a second proof attempt — was the right call.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:27:**Adversarial review (E007) justified itself.** Found a real gap (3D vs 9D eigenspace) that prevented an overclaim. Without it, the final report would have claimed a complete proof when it wasn't.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:29:## What I would do differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:33:2. **ONE approach per proof exploration, never three.** E005 presented three alternative proof approaches and the explorer stalled for 47 minutes trying to consider all three. E006 was given ONE target ("prove λ_max ≤ 64 for the 3×3 matrix") and succeeded cleanly. This is the single most important lesson.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:35:3. **Pre-check key identities before pursuing proof technique.** E008 tried to extend E006's proof to the full eigenspace without first checking whether the trace identity (heart of the proof) held for general patterns. It doesn't. Wasted an exploration. Should have had a computational pre-check step.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:41:## Surprises
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:43:- **The proof was discovered computationally, not algebraically.** The Combined Bound Lemma was found by E006 through numerical experimentation (testing subadditivity, finding it fails, then testing factorization patterns). The algebraic proof came AFTER the computational discovery. This strongly validates the "compute first" methodology.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:45:- **Partial results from failed explorations had critical downstream value.** E005 "failed" (timed out), but its 3×3 matrix reformulation was the foundation for E006's success. This is a general pattern: exploration failure != wasted budget.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:47:- **The strategizer's best decisions were deviations from the strategy.** Repurposing E006, choosing not to spend the last 2 explorations on gap closure — these improved outcomes. Good strategies should have enough structure to guide but enough flexibility for adaptation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:49:## Generalizable lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:51:1. **For proof problems, the three-phase structure works**: decompose → construct → verify. But be flexible in Phase 2 — failed proof attempts should trigger re-scoping, not mechanical adversarial review of nothing.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:53:2. **Parallel decompositions in Phase 1 are high-value** when the problem admits genuinely different algebraic perspectives. All three will usually produce something useful, and the synthesis exploration identifies which to pursue.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-conjecture-learnings.md:57:4. **Budget discipline matters.** The strategizer's decision to consolidate at 8/10 instead of chasing the last gap was correct — the marginal explorations would have needed a fundamentally different technique (SDP/SOS) better suited for a new strategy.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Learnings: Classicality Budget
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:10:## What Methodology Was Prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:12:A three-phase protocol: (1) Parallel foundation — rigorous derivation, numerical computation, and prior art search running concurrently; (2) Synthesis and stress-test — attack assumptions, identify strongest objection; (3) Implications — physical meaning, experimental tests. Designed for verifying a conjectured formula: is it correct, is it novel, is it interesting?
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:14:## How Well It Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:16:**Very well for phases 1-2, adequate for phase 3.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:18:- The parallel Phase 1 was the biggest win. Three independent explorations running simultaneously produced three orthogonal views of the same problem in the time of one. The prior art result (PARTIALLY KNOWN) informed Phase 2 design; the computation result (only constraining at Planck scale) reframed the entire problem; the derivation result (formula correct, Holevo bridge is key) was the foundation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:20:- Phase 2 stress-testing was effective. The strategizer made a smart decision to run the "strongest objection" and "operational entropy" explorations in parallel, producing the catch-22 identification AND the dramatic BH horizon result simultaneously. The catch-22 (budget valid where vacuous, interesting where invalid) was the deepest insight of the strategy.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:22:- Phase 3 was where the methodology was weakest. I prescribed "implications and experimental tests" but the strategizer focused on BH implications and holographic reformulation — both valuable, but the experimental test (a core mission requirement) was never attempted. The methodology didn't enforce coverage of the experimental question.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:24:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:26:1. **Make the experimental test exploration non-optional.** I wrote it as one possible direction in Phase 3; the strategizer chose other directions instead. For mission-critical requirements, the methodology should mandate specific explorations, not suggest them.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:28:2. **Include a "what's the most publishable finding?" phase.** The most interesting result (QD↔HQEC mapping) was discovered in the LAST exploration and wasn't developed. A methodology that asks "which of our findings has the highest value?" and then allocates 2-3 explorations to deepening it would have caught this.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:30:3. **Budget allocation guidance.** I said "10 explorations" but didn't specify minimum allocation per phase. The strategizer wisely closed at 7/10, but Phase 3 got only 2 explorations while the experimental test (Tier 5 requirement) got zero. Prescribing "Phase 3 must include at least one experimental-test exploration" would have fixed this.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:32:4. **Prior art search should include "verify novelty of each emergent finding."** My strategy only asked for prior art on the main formula. When surprising sub-results emerged (BH universal constants, QD↔HQEC mapping), their novelty wasn't verified because no prior art search was allocated for them. Future strategies should include a "verify novelty of strongest claims" step before closing.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:34:## What Surprised Me
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:36:- **The strategizer's honesty was excellent.** The FINAL-REPORT's "Honest Assessment" section was genuinely honest — "modest but genuine contribution," "not a deep new result," "mathematically elementary." This prevented overclaiming and made the result more credible. The stress-test format (requiring severity ratings with at least 2 SERIOUS) seems to have set a truth-telling norm.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:38:- **The best finding wasn't what we were looking for.** The QD↔HQEC connection (quantum Darwinism IS holographic quantum error correction) emerged from an exploration designed to resolve a technical objection (the tensor product catch-22). The most publishable result was a side effect of a stress-test fix. This suggests strategies should have "harvest surprises" checkpoints.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:40:- **Computation revealed the problem's shape faster than reasoning.** Exploration 002 (compute the numbers) immediately showed the budget is only constraining at Planck scale — a fact that would have taken much longer to figure out through reasoning alone. Exploration 005 (operational entropy) found the BH horizon constraint. Both pivots were computation-driven. Lesson: always front-load computation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:42:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:44:1. **For formula-verification missions, the derive-compute-search parallel is optimal.** These three tasks are independent and each constrains the others. The computation tells you where the formula matters; the prior art search tells you what's new; the derivation tells you what's rigorous. All three together in Phase 1 gives the strategizer maximum information for Phase 2 design.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:46:2. **Mandatory vs. suggested explorations.** If the mission has specific requirements (e.g., "identify an experimental test"), the methodology should mandate an exploration for it, not leave it as one option among many. Strategizers optimize for intellectual interest, which may not align with mission completeness.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:48:3. **The catch-22 pattern appears in fundamental physics.** When a formula depends on assumptions (tensor product structure) that break down exactly where the formula becomes interesting (Planck scale / BH horizons), this is a structural feature, not a bug. The resolution (holographic reformulation using boundary tensor product) suggests: always include a "reformulate in an alternative framework" exploration as a stress-test response.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md:50:4. **Explorer nudging is a consistent issue.** 4 of 7 explorations needed manual nudges after 3-5 minutes of 0% progress. This is a process issue that should be documented as standard operating procedure: always check explorer progress at the 3-minute mark.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:2:topic: Three-phase reconnaissance for unsolved math problems
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Learnings: Probe-Attack-Synthesize for Hard Unsolved Problems
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:10:## What the Strategy Prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:12:Three-phase "Probe-Attack-Synthesize" methodology: (1) Precision Probing — map technical obstructions at the theorem level, (2) Computational Attack — write code to test specific obstructions, (3) Synthesis — combine findings into novel contributions. Budget of 10 explorations allocated 3-4-3 (actual: 2-4-4).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:14:## How Well It Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:16:**Very well as ground-clearing. Limited for novelty production.** This matches the Riemann hypothesis missionary's finding that mapping strategies produce Tier 2-3 results but rarely Tier 1 novelty. The key difference: our computational attacks produced one genuine Tier 3 result (Adhikari-Cao bounds vacuousness) because the "computation mandatory" rule forced quantitative testing of claims.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:18:- Phase 1 (2 explorations): Efficiently mapped Balaban's program and constructive QFT landscape. The UV/IR reframing (UV solved by MRS 1993, entire difficulty is IR) was the most important strategic insight and emerged naturally from the probing methodology.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:19:- Phase 2 (4 explorations): Produced the strategy's strongest results. Lattice SU(2) simulations confirmed confinement. Finite-group convergence study was partially novel. Adhikari-Cao vacuousness computation was the most valuable output.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:20:- Phase 3 (4 explorations): Novelty search, obstruction synthesis, and adversarial review. The adversarial review (exploration 10) was the single most valuable exploration — found a real definitional error that paradoxically strengthened the main claim.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:22:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:24:1. **Mandate adversarial review at exploration 6-7, not 10.** The Δ_G definitional error was caught at the very end. If caught earlier, the remaining explorations could have used corrected values and gone deeper. Multiple meta-library entries confirm this pattern — adversarial review early is a universal lesson.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:26:2. **Bound the reconnaissance phase explicitly.** I said "~3 explorations" for Phase 1. The strategizer correctly used only 2, but this was its own good judgment, not my methodology. I should have said: "Phase 1 is ground-clearing. Maximum 3 explorations. Everything here confirms known results. Novelty starts in Phase 2."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:30:4. **Include one constructive/formalization exploration.** The mission suggested Lean formalization. Strategy 001 never attempted it. Ground-clearing + computation was natural for a first strategy, but one "attempt to prove or formalize something" exploration would have tested a different modality and possibly found hidden assumptions.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:32:5. **The RG+Bakry-Émery idea should have been tested, not just identified.** It was the most exciting output of the strategy, but it came out of exploration 9 (synthesis) with no explorations left to test it. If the synthesis phase had come at exploration 7, explorations 8-10 could have tested this computationally.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:34:## What Surprised Me
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:36:- **The strategizer's best meta-contribution was the obstruction atlas format.** The 9-approach table with classifications (TRACTABLE / FUNDAMENTAL BARRIER / HARD) and 5 bottleneck theorems is a genuinely useful artifact — more useful than any individual computation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:38:- **Explorer crashes are a real budget cost.** 3 of 10 explorations had operational issues (context pollution from other missions, tmux crash, timeout). This is a ~30% failure rate. Strategies should account for this by building in slack or having fallback plans.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:40:- **The Shen-Zhu-Zhu discovery was the most strategically important finding**, yet it wasn't what any exploration was specifically looking for. It emerged as a side-effect of the comprehensive obstruction mapping. This confirms the meta-library lesson that survey explorations at the start pay for themselves.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:42:- **Negative results can be Tier 3.** The AC vacuousness computation is a negative result (these bounds don't work) but it's quantitative, novel, and adversarially verified. The key was that it was a COMPUTATION of a negative result, not just an argument.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:44:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:46:1. **First strategy = ground-clearing; second strategy = constructive.** For hard unsolved problems, the first strategy should map the landscape and find the best attack vector. The second strategy should focus all resources on that vector. Don't try to do both at once.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:48:2. **"What exactly does [recent paper] prove?" is the highest-value probe question.** Explorations 004 and 006 (which probed Adhikari-Cao, Chatterjee, SZZ) produced the most strategically valuable output because they asked for exact theorem statements, not summaries.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:50:3. **Require mathematical specificity in the methodology, not just the goals.** "Map obstructions at the theorem level" worked better than "explore the landscape" because it forced explorers to find and state precise results.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md:54:5. **Pre-load ALL prior strategy findings into Strategy N+1.** The complete obstruction atlas, novel claims, and identified directions should be explicitly given to the next strategizer so it doesn't redo any mapping work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:8:# Strategy 002: Yang-Mills Validation — Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:10:## What was prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:12:Focused gap repair with "check numerically before proving" methodology. Phase 1: adversarial stress test of the key inequality. Phase 2: parallel proof attempts (3 paths). Phase 3: adversarial verdict. Pivot protocol if Phase 1 fails. Budget 5-6 explorations.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:14:## What worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:16:1. **"Check before prove" is correct but stress test coverage matters more than volume.** E001 tested ~300 configs and found PASS. E003 found violations in the one-hot small-angle regime that E001 missed. The lesson: a stress test with N=300 configs that all use similar perturbation types is weaker than N=50 configs with systematic coverage of perturbation types (all-link/single-link × large-angle/small-angle × random/structured).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:18:2. **3 explorations out of 5-6 budget — extremely efficient.** The strategy was designed to be conclusive early if the negative result was clear. It was. No need to burn budget on Paths A and C after E003 disproved the foundational inequality.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:22:4. **The analytical Hessian formula (E002) is a permanent result.** Even though the gap repair failed, the formula is novel and opens a direct bounding path. This is the best kind of "useful failure" — the exploration produced something valuable regardless of whether the original goal was met.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:24:5. **Strategizer's decision to skip Path A saved budget and was correct.** Path A (direct λ_max inequality) was subsumed by Path D's insights. The strategizer correctly identified this and allocated the budget elsewhere.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:26:## What didn't work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:28:1. **E001 gave a false positive.** The stress test said "PASS" but missed the critical one-hot small-angle regime. This could have led to wasted explorations on proof attempts for a false inequality. Fortunately, E003 caught it — but if E003 had been Path B (flat maximizer) without testing one-hot perturbations, we might have spent the entire budget trying to prove a false statement.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:30:2. **Pivot protocol was not needed, but was the right insurance.** The strategy included a pivot protocol for Phase 1 failure. Phase 1 "passed" (incorrectly). The pivot should have been triggered by E003's finding, but by then Phase 2 was already complete. In hindsight: the pivot protocol should have been attached to ANY exploration that finds a violation, not just Phase 1.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:32:## Generalizable lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:35:   - Random samples (volume) → catches large violations in typical regions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:36:   - Structured adversarial (types) → catches small violations in special subspaces
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:37:   - Gradient ascent → catches violations in smooth basins
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:40:2. **Gap repair strategies should be budgeted for definitive negative results.** This strategy used 3/5-6 explorations because the negative result was clear after E003. A "proof repair" strategy should always be designed so that a negative result (gap is irreparable) is a valid, valuable outcome. Don't design strategies that only succeed if the proof works.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:42:3. **Novel permanent results can emerge from failed repair attempts.** E002's analytical Hessian formula is arguably more valuable than a proof repair would have been — it's a new tool, not just a confirmation of an existing chain. Design explorations to produce reusable artifacts even if the main goal fails.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:44:4. **Two-strategy validation missions have a natural arc: audit → repair attempt.** Strategy 001 found the gap. Strategy 002 tested whether it's repairable. This is the complete validation arc. A third strategy (direct proof via new route) would be a new mission, not validation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:46:5. **Early termination on definitive negative results saves budget.** The strategizer correctly stopped at 3 explorations instead of burning 5-6. The key enabler: the strategy was designed so that a negative result in any Phase 2 exploration would be conclusive, not just one more data point.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:48:## Methodology effectiveness: 9/10
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:50:Extremely efficient — 3 explorations, all productive, definitive result. The one weakness (E001's coverage gap) was caught by E003. The analytical Hessian formula is a bonus permanent result. Budget discipline was excellent.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-003 Learnings: Finishing Strategy + Full Mission Arc
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:10:## What the strategy prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:12:A 3+1 finishing strategy: three parallel Phase 1 explorations (Santos O(ℏ²) analysis, physical-τ hydrogen rerun, 3D ZPF correlator) followed by one adversarial synthesis. Tight 4-exploration budget with no open-ended work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:14:## How well it worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:16:**Perfectly — the best-executed strategy of the three.** All four explorations delivered exactly their targets. The 3-parallel structure ran in ~35 minutes wall clock for Phase 1. The adversarial synthesis produced honest novelty assessments and caught the critical prior art (Nieuwenhuizen 2020 already stated the grand conclusion).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:18:## Key lessons from the finishing strategy
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:20:1. **Finishing strategies should be 3+1 (parallel computation + adversarial synthesis).** The 3+1 structure is the right shape when the numerical work is mostly done and you need cleanup + honest assessment. Don't leave room for "optional" explorations — the tighter the budget, the more focused the output.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:28:## Lessons from the full three-strategy arc
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:30:### The arc: depth → breadth → synthesis
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:32:| Strategy | Shape | Explorations | Achievement |
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:36:| 003 | 3 parallel cleanups + adversarial synthesis (finish) | 4 | Honest novelty assessment, mission answer |
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:38:**This arc is natural and effective for computational missions.** Strategy-001 establishes the methodology and gets the first strong result. Strategy-002 maps the frontier width. Strategy-003 ties up loose ends and does the honest reckoning.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:40:### What I'd do differently across the full mission
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:42:1. **Run the Santos connection in Strategy-002, not Strategy-003.** The Santos framework (SED = O(ℏ) QED) was the key theoretical lens for interpreting all results. Having it available during Strategy-002 would have sharpened the root cause analysis. Don't defer theoretical frameworks to the finishing strategy.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:46:3. **Budget 3 strategies from the start.** I didn't know in advance that three strategies was the right number. But the depth→breadth→synthesis arc should be plannable upfront. For future computational missions, the missionary could state: "This mission will likely need 3 strategies: one for infrastructure and first results, one for frontier mapping, one for synthesis."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:48:4. **Physical constants in STRATEGY.md.** The τ=60× bug in Strategy-002 was caught and fixed in Strategy-003, but it wasted one exploration. All physical constants should be verified and stated in STRATEGY.md, not left to explorers.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:50:### The novelty ceiling for computational survey missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:52:This mission produced Tier 3-4 results. The novelty was incremental — quantitative extensions of known qualitative results. The grand conclusion ("field quantization necessary") was prior art. This is probably the **natural ceiling for survey missions on well-studied topics.** To reach Tier 5, you'd need to either:
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:53:- Discover something genuinely unexpected (like SED succeeding where it was expected to fail)
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:54:- Derive an analytic result that explains the computational findings (convergence exponents from first principles)
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:55:- Propose and compute a new experimental test
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-sed-learnings.md:57:Survey missions produce comprehensive evidence, not breakthroughs. That's valuable — but missionaries should set expectations accordingly.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:2:topic: finishing strategy design for verification and synthesis missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-003 Thermal Time Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:10:## What was prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:12:Tight finishing strategy: 4 mandatory explorations, no early stopping. (1) Coherent state resolution of Gaussian caveat, (2) adversarial review, (3) distance-from-Gibbs systematic study, (4) final synthesis with experimental connection. Budget was intentionally tight to prevent the early-stopping problem from strategy-002.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:14:## What happened
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:16:All 4 explorations ran (the "no early stopping" rule worked). E001 resolved the Gaussian caveat definitively. E002 completed adversarial review with 4/5 novelty ratings. E003 produced a surprise — the spectrum-preservation discriminant, a NEW finding not anticipated by the strategy. E004's explorer session degraded; the strategizer wrote the synthesis directly from E001-E003 data.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:18:## What worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:20:1. **"No early stopping, all 4 mandatory" was the right constraint.** Strategy-002 stopped at 3/10 (skipping adversarial review). Strategy-003's tight budget + mandatory rule ensured all work was done. The strategizer used exactly 4 explorations. **Lesson: for finishing strategies, budget exactly the number you need and make every one mandatory.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:22:2. **The Gaussian caveat resolution design (coherent + squeezed two-tier) was excellent.** Coherent state = trivial validation (δC_local = constant, analytically predictable). Squeezed state = real test (Gaussian-exact, but non-trivial modular Hamiltonian). This two-tier design caught potential code errors early and then produced the decisive result.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:24:3. **Exploration 3 (parameter sweep) produced a surprise.** The distance-from-Gibbs characterization was designed to extend a single data point to a curve. Instead it discovered that TWO DIFFERENT curves exist (unitary vs. non-unitary deformations), yielding a new claim (spectrum-preservation discriminant, Claim 5). **Lesson: systematic parameter sweeps are discovery machines, not just verification tools.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:26:4. **Pre-loading ALL prior findings into every GOAL worked.** No explorer needed to re-derive anything from strategies 1 or 2. This saved significant time and prevented contradictions.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:28:## What didn't work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:30:1. **E004 explorer degradation.** The final synthesis explorer's session degraded and the strategizer had to write it. This is a recurring operational issue — not a methodology problem. But it means the synthesis was less rigorous than if an explorer had written it with full web search capability.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:32:2. **Explorer report-writing bottleneck persists.** Both E001 and E002 needed nudges to start writing. The meta-inbox notes say "request incremental writing" and "mandate checkpoints" — these recommendations were made but not strongly enough in the GOALs. **Lesson: the GOAL should include explicit instructions like "After completing Part A, write the Part A section to REPORT.md before starting Part B."**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:36:## Generalizable lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:38:- **The 3-strategy arc (depth → breadth → synthesis) works.** Strategy-001 closed off the obvious regime (4 explorations). Strategy-002 probed the interesting regimes (3 explorations). Strategy-003 verified, stress-tested, and synthesized (4 explorations). Total: 11 explorations across 3 strategies for a mission-complete with Tier 4-5 results.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:40:- **Finishing strategies should be tight and fully mandatory.** Budget exactly N explorations, make all mandatory, say "strategy is not complete until all N have run." This prevents the strategizer from stopping early.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:42:- **Adversarial review belongs in the finishing strategy.** Strategy-002 was supposed to include it but skipped it (early stopping). Strategy-003 made it mandatory and it ran. The structural lesson: adversarial review should be in a strategy where it CANNOT be skipped — either as the only exploration, or in a strategy with "no early stopping."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:44:- **Parameter sweeps discover things.** The distance-from-Gibbs sweep was designed to extend a data point into a curve. It discovered a qualitatively new phenomenon (two different curves, spectrum preservation as discriminant). This is the second time a "parameter sweep" exploration has produced the mission's most surprising finding (the SED tunneling R²=0.9998 was similar). Budget at least one systematic sweep per mission.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-thermal-time-learnings.md:46:- **11 explorations across 3 strategies is a natural scale for a hypothesis-testing mission.** This produced: 8-regime domain map, 2-3 novel claims at Tier 4, 1 novel interpretation, 1 experimental proposal. Enough for a publishable contribution. More explorations would hit diminishing returns.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:2:topic: Compute-first methodology for framework comparison missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:8:# Strategy 001 Learnings — Amplituhedron Mission
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:10:## The Methodology
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:12:**"Compute First, Then Break It"** — Three-phase Verify–Extend–Falsify cycle. Phase 1: compute known amplitudes both ways, build infrastructure. Phase 2: stress-test by extending beyond safe territory. Phase 3: probe for physical divergence between frameworks. Exploration design rules: every exploration must produce code, failed computations are valuable, each gets one well-scoped task.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:14:## What Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:16:1. **The three-phase structure was natural and the Strategizer followed it well.** Ground truth → extension → probing is a logical progression. The Strategizer adapted the pacing (2/10 on Phase 1 instead of suggested half), which was correct.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:18:2. **"Be brutally honest" framing in explorer goals produced excellent assessment.** Explorations that asked for honest evaluation of claims produced sharp REFORMULATION vs GENUINE CONTRIBUTION distinctions — the most valuable output of the strategy.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:20:3. **Parallel exploration launches saved time.** The Strategizer ran explorations 005 and 006 concurrently (independent topics). Good throughput optimization.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:22:4. **Early stop at 7/10 was wise.** The Strategizer recognized diminishing returns and synthesized instead of grinding out more explorations. This prevented the "one more exploration" trap.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:24:5. **Standard explorers dominated** — 5/7 explorations were literature surveys, consistently completing in ~15 min with 400-500 lines. For topics where findings are structural rather than computational, surveys beat computation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:26:## What Didn't Work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:28:1. **"Compute first" was the wrong emphasis for this domain.** The amplituhedron is a topic where the key findings are structural and conceptual — which theories it applies to, what it requires, how it relates to other programs. The most productive explorations were literature surveys, not computations. A "Survey first, then compute the interesting bits" approach would have been better.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:30:2. **The computation mandate was too strong.** The strategy said "reasoning-only explorations are failures" — but the standard explorer surveys (which were effectively reasoning + literature review) produced the best results. For framework-comparison missions, the methodology should value structured synthesis equally with computation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:32:3. **Phase 1 scope was too ambitious.** The 6-point NMHV exploration (002) tried to compute AND compare two methods AND verify. Should have been either "compute via R-invariants" OR "compare BCFW vs Grassmannian given known result." One task per exploration means one SPECIFIC task, not one general direction.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:36:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:38:1. **Match methodology to domain type.** Computational missions need "compute first." Conceptual/structural missions need "survey first, compute the gaps." The amplituhedron is a conceptual topic — the key question was "what does this framework DO?" not "what does this formula PRODUCE?" Methodology should fit the nature of the question.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:40:2. **Framework-comparison missions have a natural arc: map → characterize → probe → synthesize.** The mapping phase (which theories, which regimes) is more important than the computation phase for questions of the form "is X equivalent to Y?"
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:44:4. **One strategy can be sufficient.** For a clearly scoped question ("is X equivalent to Y?"), a single well-designed strategy with 7-10 explorations can produce a complete answer. Don't default to multi-strategy arcs when one strategy covers the landscape.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:46:5. **The computation registry is a first-class output.** The 11 identified follow-up computations (COMPUTATIONS-FOR-LATER.md) are arguably as valuable as the novel claims — they give anyone who wants to push further a concrete roadmap. Require the Strategizer to maintain this throughout, not just at the end.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md:48:6. **Budget allocation: survey-heavy is fine.** Having 5/7 explorations be literature surveys isn't a failure — it's appropriate when the domain is well-studied and the question is structural. Don't force computation for its own sake.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:2:topic: Constructive attack producing novel rigorous result
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-002 Learnings: Build-Push-Formalize for Constructive Proof Extension
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:10:## What the Strategy Prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:12:Three-phase "Build-Push-Formalize" methodology targeting the Shen-Zhu-Zhu (SZZ) Bakry-Émery mass gap extension. Budget: 10 explorations. Phase 1 (3): understand SZZ + CNS state of art. Phase 2 (4): computational Hessian slack analysis with mandatory adversarial review at E007. Phase 3 (3): proof, eigenvalue verification, large numerical scan.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:14:## How Well It Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:16:**Extremely well. Produced the mission's strongest result: a rigorous 4× improvement over the published state of the art.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:18:- Phase 1 delivered a critical strategic input: CNS (Sept 2025) already doubled SZZ from 1/48 to 1/24, making our target 1/24→better rather than 1/48→better.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:19:- Phase 2 produced the strategy's pivotal discovery: the SZZ Hessian bound is 12-138× loose, and the tight bound is H_norm = 1/12 (staggered mode at Q=I). This came from the ADVERSARIAL REVIEW (E007), not from the forward explorations.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:20:- Phase 3 proved the result rigorously (Fourier analysis at Q=I, triangle inequality for all Q → β < 1/6 proved), then numerically confirmed the stronger conditional result (β < 1/4 with 100 configs, zero counterexamples).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:22:**The original objective (RG+Bakry-Émery combination) was never tested.** The Hessian sharpness discovery redirected the entire strategy toward a simpler but more powerful approach: tighter analysis of the existing SZZ Hessian bound. This was the correct pivot — the strategizer made an excellent adaptive decision.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:24:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:30:3. **Lean formalization was correctly deprioritized.** The strategy mandated it; the strategizer rejected it as "months of work" and used the slot for eigenvalue verification instead. The strategizer was right. For a 10-exploration budget, formalization is too expensive unless the thing being formalized is simple (basic definitions). Don't mandate Lean formalization in strategies targeting proof extension.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:32:4. **Explorer long-thinking is the #1 time waste.** E007 (25 min no output) and E008 (22 min no output) each wasted ~20 min before nudges forced output. The instruction "write section by section" is insufficient — need: "Write each step as you complete it. If 5 minutes pass with no file writes, you are spending too long thinking."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:36:## What Surprised Me
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:38:- **The pivot was better than the plan.** The strategy prescribed testing RG+Bakry-Émery. The actual finding (Hessian sharpness → tighter bound) was simpler, more powerful, and required no RG machinery. The strategy's role was to point the strategizer in the right general area (SZZ extension); the strategizer's role was to find the best specific approach. This division worked perfectly.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:40:- **The adversarial review (E007) produced the most important result.** Not the proof (E008), not the computation (E005), but the adversarial review. It found the staggered mode analytically — something no forward exploration had found despite 5 prior attempts. This is the strongest argument for mandatory early adversarial review.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:42:- **A 3-exploration arc (slack discovery → adversarial tight bound → proof) is the natural unit of progress.** E005 found the slack, E007 found the tight bound, E008 proved it. Each builds on the previous. This suggests strategies should be structured around 3-exploration proof arcs with adversarial review built into the second slot.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:44:- **The rigorous result (β < 1/6) came from a weaker argument (triangle inequality) than the conjectured result (β < 1/4, Fourier).** The proved result is less impressive but more defensible. This is a feature, not a bug — the triangle inequality approach requires no conjecture.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:46:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:48:1. **Three-strategy arc works: survey → constructive attack → close the gap.** Strategy 001 mapped the landscape. Strategy 002 found the opening and partially exploited it. Strategy 003 should close the remaining proof gap.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-yang-mills-learnings.md:54:4. **The 3-exploration proof arc (discover slack → find tight bound → prove it) should be a standard methodological unit.** Build strategies around 3-exploration arcs, not individual explorations.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:2:topic: Adversarial proof audit for validation missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:8:# Strategy 001: Yang-Mills Validation — Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:10:## What was prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:12:Three-phase adversarial audit: (1) Independent rederivation + novelty assessment + convention verification in parallel, (2) Numerical extensions (large lattice, SU(3), dimensional analysis), (3) Adversarial synthesis. 8 explorations, all mandatory, adversarial posture throughout. "Try to find errors, not confirm claims."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:14:## What worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:16:1. **Adversarial posture is the most important rule for validation missions.** E007 found a genuine proof gap (Step 2: HessS formula is not an identity at generic Q). Without the adversarial mandate, this would likely have been glossed over. The gap is subtle — the formula overestimates λ_max for most Q, but the PSD inequality fails in some directions.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:18:2. **Three parallel Phase 1 explorations were perfectly scoped.** Each addressed an independent question (correctness, novelty, convention). Results cross-pollinated: E001's "counterexample" was resolved by E003's convention verification, and E002's novelty assessment was cleanly independent.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:22:4. **Phase 2 extensions produced corrections, not just confirmations.** The SU(3) exploration (E005) found N vs N² error in the conjecture. The d=5 exploration (E006) found the prior mission's odd-d formula was wrong. Validation isn't just about confirming — it's about finding the corrections.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:24:5. **190+ configurations across multiple axes (L, N, d) with 0 violations is strong evidence.** The numerical evidence is more convincing than any single proof chain, precisely because it spans multiple dimensions of the parameter space.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:26:## What didn't work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:32:3. **E008 (final synthesis) timed out.** The strategizer incorporated its work into FINAL-REPORT directly. Final synthesis explorations may be unnecessary when the strategizer has enough context. Consider making the strategizer write the final report directly instead of delegating it.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:36:## Generalizable lessons for validation missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:38:1. **Validation missions are 1-2 strategy affairs.** Strategy 001 addressed all 5 mission items. A second strategy should focus narrowly on repairing the one gap found, not re-exploring.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:40:2. **The most valuable finding in a validation mission is a SPECIFIC gap, not a vague concern.** "Step 2 is not an identity but the λ_max inequality holds numerically" is far more useful than "the proof seems fishy." Design explorations to produce specific findings.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:46:5. **Numerical extensions as Phase 2 work well because they're independent of the proof audit.** Even when the proof has a gap, the numerics remain valid evidence. The phases should be truly parallel in this sense.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:48:## Methodology effectiveness: 8/10
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-yang-mills-validation-learnings.md:50:The strategy found the gap, confirmed the novelty, corrected two errors, and covered all 5 mission items in 8 explorations. The main weakness was explorer stalling (E003, E004, E008), which the strategizer worked around effectively. The adversarial posture was the right call — without it, the proof gap would have been missed.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:2:topic: Focused-attack strategy for a quantitative gap; diminishing returns signal for mission completion
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-003 Learnings: Riemann Hypothesis
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:10:## What Methodology Was Prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:12:A focused, final strategy: "Bridging the Super-Rigidity Gap." Phase 1 attacked the gap from two independent angles (off-diagonal form factor corrections + Li criterion computation). Phase 2 deepened the best finding. Phase 3 was mandatory adversarial + synthesis. Every exploration was prescribed to target a specific quantitative question — no surveys, no open-ended construction.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:14:## How Well It Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:16:**The structure was correct but the primary attack failed for a predictable reason.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:18:- E001 (off-diagonal form factor) was designated "the single most important computation of the entire mission." It FAILED — the Berry-Keating perturbative expansion requires T >> 10^10, completely outside the regime of the first 2000 zeros (T ≈ 1682). This should have been anticipated from the asymptotic nature of the formula. The strategy put its highest-value computation on an approach that was fundamentally invalid for the available data.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:20:- E002 (Li criterion) opened a genuinely novel line — comparing Li coefficients between zeta zeros and GUE, something never done in the literature. This was the strategy's best moment. But the finding (ratio < 1 crossover) was ultimately an artifact of the comparison methodology.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:22:- The adversarial chain (E007→E008→E009) was the strategy's most valuable sequence. E007 confirmed the Li comparison was genuinely novel (4/5 novelty score). E008 found truncation sensitivity. E009 delivered the decisive refutation. This is the adversarial process working exactly as designed.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:24:- E004 (N²/p verification) correctly killed Claim A from S-002 (universality rejected). This demonstrates the value of verification explorations in later strategies.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:26:- E005 navigated to the WRONG DIRECTORY (strategy-002 instead of strategy-003). Basic operational failure that wasted an exploration. The "CWD check as Task 0" fix worked for subsequent explorations.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:28:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:30:1. **Check whether a formula is valid in the target regime BEFORE making it the centerpiece of a strategy.** Berry-Keating's perturbative expansion in powers of 1/⟨d⟩² requires ⟨d⟩ >> 1. At T=1682, ⟨d⟩ = 0.89 — the expansion diverges. A 5-minute back-of-envelope check (compute ⟨d⟩ at T=1682, compare to 1) would have flagged this. **Lesson: include a "feasibility pre-check" as exploration 0 or as a requirement before the strategy is finalized.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:34:3. **The Li coefficient investigation consumed 4 of 9 explorations (E002, E007, E008, E009) chasing what turned out to be an artifact.** The adversarial chain was correct and necessary, but it monopolized the strategy's budget. After E002 found the crossover and E007 confirmed novelty, a more efficient approach would have been: E008 = "run the decisive convergence test immediately" (which is what E009 ended up being). Instead, E008 did partial validation, required E009, and the two explorations could have been one.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:36:4. **Explorer access to papers matters.** The strategy specified "extract formulas from Berry 1985, Bogomolny-Keating 1996." Math Explorers can't access papers (no web). Standard Explorers find abstracts, not equations. The explorer had to reconstruct formulas from fragments and secondary sources, introducing errors. **Lesson: provide the key formulas DIRECTLY in the GOAL.md**, extracted from papers by the strategizer or missionary before launch.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:38:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:40:1. **Three-strategy arc (survey → construct → focus) is natural for hard unsolved problems, but expect diminishing returns.** S-001 (6 explorations, 0 claims), S-002 (9 explorations, 2 claims), S-003 (9 explorations, 0 claims, 1 prior claim retracted). The system extracts most of its value from strategies 1-2. Strategy 3 is primarily for verification, adversarial review, and closing out open questions. Don't expect new breakthroughs.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:42:2. **Verification explorations in later strategies are cheap and high-value.** E004 (N²/p verification) and E009 (Li convergence) each took one exploration and produced decisive results. Budget 1-2 verification slots in every strategy after the first.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-003-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:48:5. **24 explorations across 3 strategies may be the natural scale for a mission on a hard unsolved problem.** After that, the system has mapped the landscape, tested constructions, found what it can find, and verified its claims. Further strategies would need genuinely new mathematical ideas, not technical fixes. The "technical fixes" recommendations from the strategizer (unfolded Li comparison, K→Σ₂ normalization) are diminishing-returns work.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-002 Learnings: Parallel Probes → Root Cause → Adversarial Review
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:10:## What the strategy prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:14:## How well it worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:16:**Very well — produced the mission's strongest quantitative result.** The tunneling formula ln(Γ_SED/Γ_exact) = 0.072 + 1.049(S_WKB − √2/(4λ)) with R²=0.9998 across 4 decades is the kind of result you can present to a physicist. The breadth approach was vindicated — all three probes produced useful data, and the root cause synthesis (ω³ feedback unifies everything) only worked because we had data from 4 independent systems.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:18:6 of 10 explorations used. All produced useful results. No failures.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:20:## What I'd do differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:22:1. **Double-check physical constants in the strategy itself.** The τ value for hydrogen was wrong by 60× in the exploration goal. The missionary should have verified τ = e²/(6πε₀mₑc³) in atomic units and written it explicitly in STRATEGY.md. Cross-phase rules should include "verify all physical constants against known references before any simulation."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:24:2. **Don't prescribe "compute a modification" for Phase 2 if the literature survey is more valuable.** The strategy said to computationally test a proposed modification, but the Strategizer correctly judged that the literature survey was higher-value (it showed all known modifications fail). The methodology should have said "diagnose the root cause, using literature or computation as appropriate" rather than mandating computation for Phase 2.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:26:3. **The "minimal modification" question was the weakest part of the strategy.** It was the stated objective, but the answer was essentially "no simple modification exists — all three fixes fail." This is a valid finding but it's negative. The mission wants a constructive answer. Next strategy should flip this: instead of "what's the smallest fix for SED?", ask "what's the smallest addition to classical electrodynamics that recovers QM?" — which is Santos' ℏ-order framing.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:30:## What surprised me
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:32:- **The tunneling formula R²=0.9998 was far stronger than expected.** I designed the probes as quick surveys, not expecting any of them to produce a publishable quantitative law. The formula emerged from E001 as a conjecture and was confirmed in E005 — the two-phase discovery→verification cycle worked perfectly.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:34:- **All three probes produced novel data.** I expected at least one to be a dead end (especially hydrogen, which the library flagged as "effectively closed"). Instead, all three contributed to the root cause story.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:36:- **Prior art (Faria-França 2004) weakened the strongest claim.** The adversarial review was essential — without it, we would have overclaimed novelty for the tunneling formula.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:38:## Generalizable lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:40:1. **Parallel probes for frontier mapping is a strong methodology.** When you need to characterize a boundary across multiple independent systems, launch them all simultaneously. The root cause synthesis is only possible when you have data from diverse domains.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:42:2. **The two-strategy arc (depth then breadth, or breadth then depth) is natural for computational missions.** Strategy-001 went deep on one system, Strategy-002 went wide across three. The combination is more powerful than either alone.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-sed-learnings.md:46:4. **Physical constant verification should be a cross-phase rule.** When simulations use physical units, wrong constants invalidate results even if the code is correct.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:2:topic: Adversarial Derivation Protocol for hypothesis-testing missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Learnings: Compton-Unruh Resonance
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:10:## Methodology: Adversarial Derivation Protocol
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:12:Prescribed a three-phase protocol: (1) Framework & Feasibility — dimensional analysis + no-go search, (2) Calculation & Prediction — compute key equations + generate numbers, (3) Distinctness & Stress Testing — compare with prior work + adversarial test. Core principle: "derive, then immediately try to kill what you derived."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:14:## What Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:16:### Dimensional analysis as Phase 1 gatekeeper was the best decision
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:18:The very first exploration killed the original hypothesis by 43 orders of magnitude. Without this, the strategy would have spent 7 explorations building on a dimensionally impossible foundation. **Lesson: For any hypothesis-testing mission, mandate dimensional analysis / feasibility check as exploration 001.** This is cheap (one math exploration) and can save the entire budget if the hypothesis is dead.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:20:### Math explorers for computation were 4/4
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:24:### Parallel exploration pairs were efficient
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:26:The strategizer effectively paired explorations: (001 dimensional analysis + 002 literature survey), (005 novelty search + 006 FDT mechanism), (007 free-fall + 008 adversarial). This doubled throughput when tasks were independent. **Lesson: Parallel pairs work well when the two tasks are genuinely independent — don't pair things where one result should inform the other.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:28:### The pivot was handled well
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:30:When exploration 001 killed the original hypothesis, the strategizer pivoted to the de Sitter crossover — the one feature at the right scale. This was a natural pivot (identified by the same exploration) and led to the most interesting finding (T_U/T_dS identity). **Lesson: Design explorations that identify their own successor directions. Ask "what IS at the right scale?" not just "is THIS at the right scale?"**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:32:## What I'd Change
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:34:### Run the adversarial test MUCH earlier
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:36:The adversarial stress test (exploration 008) found a fatal flaw — Bullet Cluster lensing — that was a *standard test*. This should have been exploration 003 or 004, not 008. Seven constructive explorations built on the T_U/T_dS identity before discovering it was falsified. The modified-inertia-doesn't-modify-lensing objection is well-known in the field. **Lesson: In the methodology, mandate an adversarial/falsification exploration no later than the third or fourth slot. Don't wait until Phase 3. Phrase it as: "What is the single strongest observational test that could kill this? Run it now."**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:38:### The 1/(2π) investigation was predictable wasted time
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:40:The strategizer sent exploration 007 to derive the factor of 1/(2π) from the T_U/T_dS ratio. This was algebraically doomed: 2π appears identically in both T_U and T_dS and cancels in the ratio. A 30-second algebra check would have caught this. **Lesson: In the methodology, add a pre-launch algebra/dimensional check: "Before launching an exploration, verify that the question isn't trivially answerable. If the answer follows from the formula's structure in 5 minutes of algebra, don't spend an exploration on it."**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:42:### Context contamination in parallel launches
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:46:## Surprising Observations
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:48:### The most interesting finding was a side-effect of the pivot
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:52:### The strategizer self-corrected well
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:56:### One strategy was sufficient for this mission
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:58:8 explorations (6 successful, 1 failed, 1 adversarial) reached all 5 validation tiers. The mission asked a yes/no question (does the resonance modify inertia?) and got a decisive no. **Lesson: For hypothesis-testing missions with clear falsification criteria, one well-designed strategy can be enough. Don't plan for multiple strategies if the question has a binary answer.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:60:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:62:1. **Dimensional analysis first.** Always. For any quantitative hypothesis.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:63:2. **Adversarial tests early, not late.** Run the strongest falsification test as soon as there's something to falsify. Don't build for 7 explorations before stress-testing.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md:64:3. **Pre-launch algebra check.** If the question is trivially answerable from the formula's structure, answer it before spending an exploration.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:2:topic: Dual-track obstruction+construction strategies for impossibility proofs
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-002 Learnings: Vasseur Pressure Exponent
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:10:## Context
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:11:Mission: Close the De Giorgi recurrence exponent gap β = 4/3 → β > 3/2 for Navier-Stokes regularity. Strategy-002 was the constructive "attack" phase following Strategy-001's "map" phase. 8 of 20 explorations used. Result: β = 4/3 is SHARP — proven impossible to improve within the De Giorgi framework.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:13:## Lesson 1: Phase 0 "decomposition audit" is the single highest-leverage exploration type for proof-improvement missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:14:Phase 0 (E001) read Vasseur's proof line-by-line and classified each step as sharp or potentially loose. Result: 4 of 5 steps provably sharp, 1 potentially loose (Chebyshev). This IMMEDIATELY closed 3 of 5 planned Track B directions before a single attack exploration ran. **For any mission targeting improvement of a known proof, start with a line-by-line audit that classifies each step's improvability.** This is more valuable than Phase 0 "gates" — it doesn't just check feasibility, it eliminates most attack directions upfront.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:16:## Lesson 2: Dual-track (obstruction + construction) is the optimal structure for "can we improve X?" missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:17:Strategy-002 ran Track A (prove the barrier is universal) and Track B (try to break it) concurrently. They converged on the same answer from opposite directions: Track A discovered β = 1+s/n (the barrier IS universal), Track B closed eight routes (the barrier CANNOT be broken). **When the question is "can X be improved?", always run both tracks.** If the answer is yes, Track B produces the improvement and Track A provides the counterexample showing where it works. If the answer is no, Track A produces the obstruction theorem and Track B provides the exhaustive negative evidence. Either way, both tracks contribute.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:19:## Lesson 3: Direction Status Tracker prevents budget waste and enables clean stopping
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:20:The Direction Status Tracker (a table maintained in REASONING.md after each exploration) was new for Strategy-002. It worked flawlessly — the Strategizer could see at a glance which directions were open, closed, or promising. This enabled confident early stopping at 8/20 budget when all directions showed CLOSED. **Prescribe a Direction Status Tracker in every strategy.** It's a small overhead (one table update per exploration) with large payoff (prevents revisitation, enables clean stopping, provides at-a-glance strategy status).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:22:## Lesson 4: The "two-strategy arc" completed successfully — map then attack is the right pattern for impossibility results
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:23:Strategy-001 (10 explorations) mapped the obstruction landscape. Strategy-002 (8 explorations) attacked it constructively. The result is a clean impossibility proof with both positive evidence (sharpness proof) and negative evidence (eight closed routes). **The map→attack arc produces the strongest impossibility results** because the attack phase is focused (map tells you WHERE to attack) and the map phase provides context that makes the attack's negative results interpretable. Cumulative: 18 explorations, two strategies, one clean result.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:25:## Lesson 5: Explorers can simplify goals — don't over-specify the computational approach
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:26:E008 was designed as an SDP relaxation (~100 lines CVXPY). The explorer found a one-line extremizer (constant div-free field) that made the SDP unnecessary. **When designing computation-focused explorations, state the mathematical question and let the explorer choose the tool.** The SDP specification was a backup, not a requirement — and the explorer's simpler solution was far more elegant and convincing.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:28:## Lesson 6: Parallel exploration launches have minor context-gap costs that are worth paying
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:29:E006 and E007 launched in parallel. E007 (adversarial review) flagged "non-CZ pressure handling incomplete" — but E006 had already completed it. This is a minor context gap from parallel launching. **The cost is negligible** — the reviewer flagged one extra item that was already done. The benefit (two explorations completing in the time of one) far outweighs this.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:31:## What I'd do differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:32:1. **Nothing major.** This was the cleanest strategy across both missions. Phase 0 audit, Direction Status Tracker, dual-track structure, and clean stopping all worked.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Barandes-Stochastic: Missionary Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:10:## Mission Type
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:13:## What the Methodology Was
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:15:- Phase 1 (3 planned, 2 used): Framework extraction + stochastic programs comparison
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:16:- Phase 2 (3 planned, 2 used): Phase freedom computation + physical content probe
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:17:- Phase 3 (2 planned, 2 used): Adversarial review + steelman
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:20:- Pre-loaded 6 adversarial findings from a prior mission (QG-2) into every exploration goal
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:21:- Required "quote, don't paraphrase" for all framework claims
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:22:- Cross-phase rule: "compute, don't argue"
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:23:- Mandatory adversarial review with steelman requirement
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:24:- Explorer type prescription (standard vs math) for each exploration
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:26:## What Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:28:### Pre-loading adversarial context is the highest-leverage strategy design move for framework analysis missions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:29:The QG-2 mission had already produced 6 adversarial findings about Barandes. By injecting these directly into the strategy's "Prior Knowledge" section and requiring every explorer to engage with them, the first exploration resolved 4 of 5 objections — saving an entire exploration (the planned E003 "Adversarial Disambiguation" became unnecessary). This is the most efficient pattern I've seen: instead of discovering objections, verify or refute pre-existing ones.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:31:**Generalizable lesson:** If a prior mission or strategy has already assessed any aspect of the current target, pre-load those findings with explicit instructions to "adjudicate, not rediscover." This saves 1-2 explorations.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:33:### One strategy can suffice for well-scoped "is this X?" questions
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:34:The mission question — "is Barandes just notation?" — has a definitive answer (Level 2+ reformulation). One strategy with 6 explorations produced this verdict. The amplituhedron and Compton-Unruh meta-learnings predicted this: clearly scoped evaluation questions don't need iterative strategies.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:36:**Generalizable lesson:** For evaluation missions ("is X valid?", "does X add something?", "is X equivalent to Y?"), plan for one strategy. Two is overkill unless the first strategy discovers the question is more complex than expected.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:38:### The strategizer's decision to compress Phase 1 was correct and should be anticipated
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:39:The strategy allocated 3 explorations to Phase 1. The strategizer used 2 — E001 was so thorough (with pre-loaded adversarial context) that E003 became redundant. The saving was reinvested into Phase 2.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:41:**Generalizable lesson:** When pre-loading adversarial context into framework extraction explorations, expect Phase 1 to compress. Design the strategy so the saved exploration can be redeployed to Phase 2.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:43:### Steelman requirement transforms adversarial reviews
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:46:### Three-level classification emerged from the comparison exploration — not from the strategy
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:47:The most useful organizing insight (Level 1/2/3 = Physical/Formal/Interpretational) was generated by E002, not prescribed by the strategy. The strategy asked for comparisons along structured dimensions; the explorer synthesized the classification independently. Good strategies create the conditions for synthesis without prescribing the synthesis itself.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:49:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:51:### Should have included the most promising computation explicitly
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:52:The Tsirelson non-unistochastic question is a well-defined computational problem (enumerate ISPs on 4×4 stochastic matrix, apply causal locality, optimize CHSH). The strategizer identified it in E005 as the "single most important open question" but didn't run it. The strategy should have anticipated that for reformulation programs, the most interesting computation is not "verify the correspondence" but "test the extension beyond the correspondence."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:54:**Generalizable lesson:** For reformulation/framework analysis missions, include a Phase 2 exploration explicitly targeting: "What computation, if run successfully, would upgrade this reformulation to new physics? Design and run that computation." This is the highest-value question and should not be left to the strategizer's discretion — it should be structurally required.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:56:### Concrete worked example may have been worth doing despite the gap analysis shortcut
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:57:The strategizer skipped the side-by-side QM↔ISP worked example (Strategy E4) because the gap analysis (ISP erases phases → strictly less informative) answered the equi-informativeness question. This was probably correct, but a concrete computation showing the same qubit system in both formalisms would have been more pedagogically convincing and might have revealed structural details the gap analysis missed.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:59:**Generalizable lesson:** For framework analysis missions, always include at least one side-by-side worked example, even if abstract arguments already answer the question. Concrete examples catch things abstractions miss.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:61:### Math explorer path confusion is still a problem
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:64:## Surprising Observations
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:66:1. **The strategizer never queried the librarian after E002.** It had enough context from E001-E002 to design all remaining goals without library queries. This suggests that for focused missions with pre-loaded context, the library is most valuable at the start and becomes redundant midway through.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-barandes-stochastic-learnings.md:70:3. **6 of 8 explorations used.** The strategizer had budget remaining and correctly assessed diminishing returns. Good strategies build in budget slack; great strategizers know when to stop early.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Learnings: Vasseur Pressure Exponent
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:10:## Context
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:11:Mission: Close the De Giorgi recurrence exponent gap β = 4/3 → β > 3/2 for Navier-Stokes regularity. Strategy-001 was a ground-clearing "Verify → Measure → Characterize" strategy. 10 of 20 explorations used. Result: Path B (gap is genuine, 4/3 barrier is structural).
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:13:## Lesson 1: Phase 0 "redefine the target" is as valuable as Phase 0 "gate the target"
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:14:The prior missions taught us that Phase 0 gates save entire strategies. This mission adds a complementary lesson: Phase 0 can REDEFINE the target, not just verify it. Exploration 001 revealed that β is a recurrence exponent, not a pressure integrability exponent — fundamentally different from what we assumed. This redefinition made the Phase 1 explorations much more targeted (measuring P_k^{21} specifically, not general pressure slack). **Prescribe Phase 0 goals that ask "what EXACTLY are we measuring?" not just "can we measure it?"**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:16:## Lesson 2: "Follow leads before adversarial review" should be prescribed, not improvised
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:17:The strategizer correctly deviated from the strategy to insert Phase 1b/1c (4 explorations following leads from Phase 1) before the adversarial review. This was good judgment — the adversarial review would have just flagged these as unexplored leads. **Future strategies should include a "Lead Pursuit" phase between measurement and adversarial review as a prescribed option:** "If Phase 1 surfaces promising leads, the Strategizer may run up to N additional explorations before Phase 2, provided each is a single-task, literature-or-computation goal."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:19:## Lesson 3: The "adversarial → targeted test" sequence is the strongest quality pattern
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:22:## Lesson 4: Negative results from multiple independent angles = strong obstruction evidence
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:23:Strategy-001 established the 4/3 barrier through 5 independent angles: (1) DNS β_eff < 4/3, (2) CZ slack k-independent, (3) Galilean invariance irrelevant, (4) 4/3 reappears in pressure-free vorticity formulation, (5) 17 years of literature with no improvement. No single angle is definitive, but together they strongly constrain the problem space. **For obstruction mapping, design Phase 1 with deliberately diverse angles of attack.** If they all return negative, the obstruction is well-established. If one breaks through, the others provide triangulation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:25:## Lesson 5: "Mechanism works for exact X" ≠ "mechanism works for near-X"
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:26:The Beltrami mechanism was the strategy's most promising lead (3 explorations invested). It was structurally correct (Lamb vector = 0 eliminates CZ loss) but specific to exact Beltrami (measure-zero). Even 1% perturbation killed it. **For any conditional regularity approach, test generalization EARLY, before investing multiple explorations in the exact case.** The E010 perturbation sweep should have been E007, not E010.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:28:## Lesson 6: Budget efficiency is enhanced by negative results being genuinely terminal
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:29:10 of 20 budget used. Clean stopping was possible because each negative result clearly closed a direction. The methodology's cross-phase rules (multi-IC validation, convergence checks) meant each negative was trustworthy. **Invest in making negative results DEFINITIVE (multi-IC, convergence-checked, multi-angle) so that directions stay closed. Ambiguous negatives lead to revisitation and wasted budget.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:31:## What I'd do differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-vasseur-pressure-learnings.md:35:4. Add a "direction status" tracking table that the strategizer maintains and updates after each exploration (OPEN/CLOSED/PROMISING/EXHAUSTED for each direction)
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:2:topic: Constraint-catalog methodology for hard unsolved problems; verification vs. novelty tradeoff
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-001 Learnings: Riemann Hypothesis
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:10:## What Methodology Was Prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:12:A three-phase "Computational Constraint Cartography" protocol: (1) Extract mathematical constraints from multiple domains, each backed by computation; (2) Test specific operator candidates against the constraint catalog; (3) Synthesis and adversarial review. Designed for a hard unsolved problem where mapping the landscape first seemed prudent.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:14:## How Well It Worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:16:**Good for ground-clearing, poor for novelty production.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:18:- Phase 1 was effective. Two explorations built a 10-point quantitative constraint catalog with reproducible code. The "every constraint must have a computation" rule was the strongest design choice — it prevented literature-summary explorations and produced concrete, verifiable results.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:20:- Phase 2 produced useful negative results. All known Berry-Keating xp regularizations score 0/10 against the catalog. The trace formula reconstruction found a deep structural limitation (Gibbs phenomenon). Real symmetric arithmetic matrices can't reach GUE. These are all correct and well-characterized, but they're confirming what experts already know.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:22:- Phase 3 was completely skipped. The strategizer wrote the final report after Phase 2 without running any synthesis or adversarial explorations. This is the biggest methodology failure: the strategy allocated 10 explorations but only used 6, and the most intellectually valuable phase (synthesis) was never attempted.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:24:## What I'd Do Differently
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:26:1. **"Verify known results" is a valid Phase 1, but the strategy should have explicitly bounded it.** I should have written: "Phase 1 is ground-clearing. Everything here will confirm known results. The novelty comes in Phases 2 and 3." Instead, the entire strategy turned into Phase 1 work — testing known candidates against known predictions. A domain expert would recognize every finding as already published.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:28:2. **Make Phase 3 (adversarial + synthesis) MANDATORY with minimum allocations.** The strategizer optimized for intellectual interest in Phase 2 and ran out of steam before Phase 3. Prescribe: "At minimum, exploration N-1 MUST be adversarial review and exploration N MUST be synthesis."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:30:3. **The methodology should force constructive work, not just testing.** "Test candidates against constraints" is backward-looking by nature. A strategy for a hard unsolved problem needs at least some explorations that attempt something that hasn't been done. "Build an operator" is different from "test known operators."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:32:4. **Scope the computation platform in the strategy.** Every exploration was limited by mpmath's ~2000-zero ceiling. If I'd specified "use precomputed zero tables from LMFDB or Odlyzko (millions of zeros)" in the strategy, the numerical results would have been 100x more precise and potentially novel in their precision.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:36:## What Surprised Me
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:38:- **The strategizer's self-evaluation was accurate and honest.** The FINAL-REPORT says "No genuinely novel claims emerged that would survive expert scrutiny." This is correct. The honest assessment is valuable — no overclaiming.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:40:- **The chain of reasoning across explorations was the most valuable output**, not any individual finding. GUE confirmed → super-rigidity from primes → xp alone fails → trace formula gives density not correlations → arithmetic matrices need complex structure. Each step constrained the next. This "insight chain" was emergent, not planned.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:42:- **The constraint catalog was used as a checklist rather than a generative tool.** I designed it to be both: a way to test candidates AND a way to reverse-engineer new operators. The strategizer only used it as a checklist. Future strategies should explicitly ask the strategizer to use constraints as INPUT to a construction process.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:44:- **Six of ten explorations were used.** The strategizer closed early because it felt it had exhausted the approach. This is actually good judgment — the remaining budget would have produced more negative results in the same frame. But the unused budget should have gone to synthesis/adversarial, not been left idle.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:46:## Generalizable Lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:48:1. **For hard unsolved problems, "map the landscape" strategies produce Tier 2-3 results (rigorous, evidenced) but not Tier 1 (novel).** Domain experts already know the landscape. Novelty requires going beyond the map — constructing, combining, or computing something that hasn't been done. Strategy-001 should have been the ground-clearing half of a two-strategy arc.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:50:2. **The "constraint catalog" format is excellent for Phase 1-2 work.** It gives the strategizer a concrete, growing artifact to reference and a quantitative success metric for candidates. But it must be coupled with a constructive phase that uses the catalog as input.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:52:3. **Negative results are valuable but only once.** "xp regularizations fail" is useful. "Trace formula can't reconstruct individual zeros" is useful. But a whole strategy of negative results doesn't advance the mission. One ground-clearing strategy is enough; strategy-002 must be constructive.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:54:4. **Computation scale matters more than computation count.** Five explorations with 2000 zeros each produce five confirmations of known results. One exploration with a million zeros might produce a genuinely novel measurement. Prescribe the data scale in the strategy, not just "compute."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md:56:5. **Parallel Phase 1 explorations (from classicality-budget learnings) would have helped here too.** The first two explorations were sequential but independent. Running them in parallel would have freed budget for Phase 3.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:2:topic: Constructive proof strategy with Phase 0 gating
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-002 Navier-Stokes Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:10:## What the methodology was
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:12:Three-phase **Validate Premise → Construct Proof → Adversarial Verification** with a Phase 0 gate (clear go/no-go criterion: T_BKM/T_Lad > 10). One theorem target per exploration. Mandatory math + standard adversarial review. 4 of 20 explorations used.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:14:## What worked exceptionally well
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:16:1. **Phase 0 gating with quantitative criterion.** The success threshold (T_BKM/T_Lad > 10) was clear, unambiguous, and exceeded by a factor of 10⁶. This immediately validated the entire strategic direction and meant no pivoting was needed. **For constructive strategies following ground-clearing, always include a quantitative Phase 0 gate.** If the gate fails, you save 15+ explorations. If it passes (as here), you proceed with confidence.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:18:2. **"ONE theorem per exploration, state first, prove second."** Exploration 002 stated the BKM enstrophy theorem, then proved it in 4 steps. The proof gap (BGW on T³) was identified precisely. This produced a clean, reviewable result. **This instruction format works — use it for all proof explorations.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:20:3. **Ground-clearing → constructive arc.** Strategy-001 (8 explorations) mapped the landscape. Strategy-002 (4 explorations) attacked the best target. The 2:1 ratio of ground-clearing to constructive explorations is about right for a well-characterized problem. **The two-strategy arc is the natural pattern for Millennium-adjacent problems: map → attack.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:22:4. **Killing dead ends immediately.** The C(F₄) direction was killed in exploration 003 via the exact algebraic identity. No time wasted on further investigation. **Always check for algebraic identities behind empirical correlations before making them a strategy direction.** This was knowable before Strategy-002 was designed — a 3-line calculation. The lesson: missionary should verify key empirical findings computationally before building a strategy around them.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:24:5. **4 of 20 explorations — stopping when done.** The strategizer recognized that the strategy's goals were met and stopped. This takes discipline. Budget efficiency across both strategies: 12 of 40 possible explorations. **"Done" is not "budget exhausted" — it's "goals met or obstruction identified."**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:26:## What didn't work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:28:1. **Math adversarial review was prescribed but not done.** The strategy called for both a math explorer adversarial recomputation AND a standard adversarial review. Only the standard review was done. The strategizer judged 4 explorations sufficient and skipped the math adversarial. **This is a recurring pattern: when budgets are tight, adversarial recomputation gets cut first.** Consider making math adversarial mandatory by placing it before the strategizer's completion decision, not after.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:30:2. **Protas-type adversarial IC search not done.** This would have been the strongest validation of Claim 1. It was listed as optional (Phase 2C, "if budget allows"), and budget was allocated elsewhere. **If a validation step is important enough to include in the strategy, make it non-optional or accept its absence in the final assessment.** Don't put critical validations in "if budget allows" slots.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:32:3. **C(F₄) direction should have been killed before becoming a strategy direction.** The algebraic identity C_Leff⁴ = F₄ · R³ is trivially derivable from the definitions. The missionary (me) should have checked this before including it as Direction B. **Missionary should computationally verify key empirical claims from prior strategies before building the next strategy around them.** A 5-minute sub-agent computation would have caught this.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:34:4. **Explorer output latency (30+ minutes before first file written).** All four explorations had the same pattern: 20-30 minutes of reading/thinking/coding before producing any output file. The "write section by section" instruction in the goals was consistently ignored. **This appears to be a structural limitation of the explorer prompt, not a strategy design issue.** The meta-inbox notes all flag it. Consider requiring "create REPORT.md skeleton IMMEDIATELY after reading goal" in the explorer system prompt itself.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:36:## Surprising findings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:38:- **The BKM advantage was 10⁶-10¹⁵× larger than expected.** I designed the Phase 0 gate at T_BKM/T_Lad > 10, expecting 10-100×. The actual advantage is 10⁷ to 10¹⁶. This is because the ν⁻³ factor in the Ladyzhenskaya ODE is catastrophic at high Re. The lesson: when designing Phase 0 gates, set the threshold conservatively. Being surprised on the upside is fine; being surprised by a marginal result requires re-evaluation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:40:- **The "logical circle" is the most important strategic finding.** The adversarial reviewer identified that BKM enstrophy → regularity requires ||ω||_{L^∞} control → which IS the BKM criterion → which is equivalent to regularity. This means no enstrophy-based approach can prove regularity — the entire direction has a structural ceiling. **This kind of "impossibility identification" is as valuable as a positive result. It saves future strategies from attacking a provably closed direction.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:42:- **C(F₄) killed by algebra, not physics.** The Strategy-001 empirical correlation was between algebraically linked quantities along a single trajectory. This is a pure statistics mistake (confounding variables), not a physics insight. **Lesson: always check whether your regression variables are algebraically dependent before interpreting a correlation as causal.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:44:## Lessons that generalize
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:46:1. **Two-strategy arc for hard problems: map (8-10 explorations) → attack (4-6 explorations).** The ground-clearing strategy produces Tier 2-3. The constructive strategy attempts Tier 4-5. If the attack succeeds, you're done. If it identifies a structural obstruction, you're also done (differently). This is now validated on Navier-Stokes, Yang-Mills, and Riemann missions.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:48:2. **Phase 0 gates save or validate entire strategies.** Set quantitative thresholds. If the gate passes overwhelmingly (as here), the strategy proceeds with confidence and minimal pivoting. If it fails, you save 80% of the budget. Phase 0 is the highest-ROI exploration in a constructive strategy.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:52:4. **Structural impossibilities (logical circles, Tao obstructions) are permanent findings.** They constrain all future strategies, not just the current one. Document them prominently in MISSION-COMPLETE.md and the library.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-navier-stokes-learnings.md:54:5. **"Modest but genuine" novelty is the realistic ceiling for well-studied problems.** The BKM enstrophy theorem is correct, proved, computationally verified, and adversarially reviewed — but experts would consider it "obvious." The quantitative slack atlas (237×) has higher novelty precisely because nobody bothered to measure it before. **Sometimes the most novel contribution is not a theorem but a measurement.**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:1:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:6:---
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:8:# Strategy-002 Thermal Time Learnings
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:10:## What was prescribed
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:12:Three mandatory parallel computational probes: (1) Rindler vacuum verification (control), (2) non-equilibrium post-quench test, (3) excited-state modular flow in QFT. Followed by a deepen phase and mandatory adversarial review. Budget: 6 explorations across 3 phases.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:14:## What happened
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:16:The strategizer launched all 3 probes simultaneously. All 3 succeeded with decisive results. The strategizer correctly stopped after Phase 1 (3 explorations total), deeming the results sufficient for a final report. Phases 2 and 3 (deepen, adversarial, synthesis) were never executed.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:18:## What worked
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:20:1. **All-mandatory parallel probes are the ideal Phase 1 design.** Three independent probes, all mandatory, all computational, all successful. Zero waste. The Yang-Mills and SED meta-lessons about "all explorations mandatory (no optional)" were validated again.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:22:2. **Naming the probes explicitly in the strategy worked better than abstract methodology.** Each probe was a specific, well-defined computation. The strategizer translated them directly into GOALs. No ambiguity, no wasted iterations deciding what to do.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:26:4. **The "control test" (Rindler vacuum) paid off immediately.** It caught a physics error in the GOAL (modular flow = boost, not time translation), which would have contaminated the other probes' interpretation.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:28:## What didn't work
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:30:1. **The strategizer stopped too early.** 3 of 10 budgeted explorations used. No adversarial review, no coherent-state test, no synthesis. The results were strong enough that the strategizer felt done — but the Gaussian approximation caveat on the strongest claim (Claim 3) is a real gap that should have been resolved before declaring the strategy complete.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:32:2. **The strategy should have made the adversarial review non-deferrable.** It was listed as "Phase 2, exploration 5: MANDATORY adversarial review" — but "mandatory" within a phase that the strategizer chose to skip. **Lesson: if adversarial review is truly mandatory, it should be Phase 1 (not Phase 2) or structurally enforced (e.g., "strategy is not complete until the adversarial exploration runs").**
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:34:3. **The coherent-state fallback for E003 was mentioned as a "Direction B recommendation" instead of a built-in escalation.** The Gaussian approximation was a known risk. The strategy should have said: "If the one-particle result uses Gaussian approximation, ALSO test with a coherent state in the same exploration."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:36:## Generalizable lessons
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:38:- **Parallel mandatory probes + pre-loaded context is the highest-efficiency methodology pattern.** Three probes, three successes, zero waste. This pattern should be the default for Phase 1 of any computational strategy.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:40:- **Adversarial review MUST be structurally enforced, not just labeled "mandatory."** If it's in Phase 2 and Phase 1 results are clean, the strategizer will skip it. Either include it as one of the parallel Phase 1 probes (running on prior-strategy claims), or add a structural rule: "strategy cannot be marked complete without an adversarial exploration."
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:42:- **Approximation caveats must have built-in resolution paths.** If a computation uses an approximation (Gaussian, perturbative, finite-size), the GOAL should include: "Also run the exact version on a simpler case to bound the approximation error." This prevents the caveat from surviving into the final report.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:44:- **Early stopping by strategizers is a mixed signal.** Strategy-002 stopped at 3/10 explorations. The results were genuinely decisive — but the remaining work (adversarial, coherent test) would have strengthened the claims significantly. Missionaries should either (a) budget tighter (5 explorations, all mandatory) to prevent premature stopping, or (b) include an explicit "minimum exploration count" rule.
../../agents/library/meta/missionary/strategy-002-thermal-time-learnings.md:46:- **Physics errors in GOALs get caught but waste time.** E001's GOAL confused modular flow with time translation. The explorer caught it and corrected course — but this cost time and could have been worse. For relativistic / QFT problems, the strategy must specify which symmetry generator is being compared. "Compare to full QM" is ambiguous when there are multiple notions of time.

